					<h2>Before You Sign, Close, or Commit—Ask Yourself:
</h2>				
							<ul>
							<li>
										 Does my contract fully protect my interests, not just theirs?
									</li>
								<li>
										 Am I using the right entity for tax protection and liability?
									</li>
								<li>
										 What happens if this property has a title defect, lien, or prior claim?
									</li>
								<li>
										 Do I know the legal steps if there’s a probate, foreclosure, or dispute?
									</li>
								<li>
										 Who’s helping me avoid problems—not just clean up the mess after?
									</li>
						</ul>
					<h2>What Happens Without the Right Legal or Title Help?
</h2>				
							<ul>
							<li>
										You inherit surprise tax bills, liens, or lawsuits
									</li>
								<li>
										Your contract leaves you vulnerable to non-refundable deposits or contingency gaps
									</li>
								<li>
										You buy a home—only to discover someone else legally owns part of it
									</li>
								<li>
										You set up your business deal improperly and get flagged by the SEC
									</li>
								<li>
										You go through a divorce or family death and find yourself locked in a messy probate
									</li>
						</ul>
					<h3>Why a Great Title Team Matters</h3>				
		<p>A skilled title team does more than paperwork — they protect your investment, uncover hidden risks, and ensure your closing stays on track.</p>		
									<h3>
							Uncover What You Can’t See						
					</h3>
									<p>
						Expose hidden liens, easements, boundary issues, title gaps, and unpaid taxes.
Catch encumbrances and fraud early—protecting your closing and future resale.					</p>
									<h3>
							Streamline &amp; Safeguard Closings						
					</h3>
									<p>
						From lien payoffs and wire transfers to 1031 exchanges and digital notary services, your title team handles the paperwork and protects your timeline.
					</p>
									<h3>
							Protect Your Investment Long-Term						
					</h3>
									<p>
						Title insurance is often overlooked—but essential. It guards your ownership, ensuring the property remains legally and financially secure for years to come.					</p>
					<h2>Here’s what can go wrong:
</h2>				
							<ul>
							<li>
										Entity Formation (LLCs, Trusts, Partnerships)
									</li>
								<li>
										Contract Review &amp; Risk Mitigation
									</li>
								<li>
										Probate, Divorce &amp; Inherited Properties
									</li>
								<li>
										You set up your business deal improperly and get flagged by the SEC
									</li>
								<li>
										SEC-Compliant Deal Structuring (506b/506c syndications)
									</li>
						</ul>
